        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-11-01T18:26:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-11-01T18:26:00-05:00" n="83"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d83">
                <head>83. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d83fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 700.5611/10–2855. Confidential; Priority. Drafted by Meyers and
                        approved by <persName corresp="#p_BNW1">Bond</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-11-01T18:26:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 1, 1955—6:26 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_GADel2">Gadel</gloss> 76. Re radiation (<gloss
                        target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 175).<note n="2" xml:id="d83fn2">
                        <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 175 from New York, October 28,
                        indicated that the problem of a moratorium on nuclear tests would probably
                        arise during the forthcoming debate on radiation and asked for instructions.
                        Since the Soviets had urged cessation of tests in their May 10 proposals as
                        well as in their suggested amendments to the radiation resolution, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> said it would be useful if he could
                        say that the United States supported cessation of tests as part of a
                        comprehensive disarmament system. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>.)</note>
                    USDEL can make following statement on moratorium: “The US believes that a
                    moratorium on tests of nuclear weapons is an inseparable part of the disarmament
                    problem and cannot be dealt with alone. Any agreed disarmament program must be
                    predicated on equitable and effective inspection and control systems applicable
                    to all elements of this agreed disarmament program. This moratorium question is,
                    consequently, properly part of the efforts to reach agreement on disarmament
                    carried on in the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Disarmament Commission, its
                    Subcommittee and other areas.”</p>
                <p>Foregoing is maximum we believe USDEL could say on this problem now in light
                    present stage disarmament review.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHCJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Hoover</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
